<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12093h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12093h">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12093h"> 93(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ don&apos;t wake the children</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Selon les r&egrave;gles de la politesse du pays, on ne leur adresse aucune question et on les laisse causer; il est toutefois d&apos;usage de leur offrir <font color="green">[351]</font> &agrave; manger du lard ou du boeuf sal&eacute;. On cause d&apos;abord des choses les plus diverses, except&eacute; du mariage; &agrave; la fin cependant, le p&egrave;re (ou le proche parent venu avec le jeune homme) fait la demande aux parents de la jeune fille. A ce moment, le galant sort de son panier la bouteille d&apos;eau-de-vie (dans le pays de Lannion c&apos;est une bouteille de vin blanc) et en offre &agrave; toutes les personnes pr&eacute;sentes de tout &acirc;ge et de tout sexe, sauf aux tout petits enfants qu&apos;on n&apos;a pas r&eacute;veill&eacute;s. <br><font color="green">[According to the country&apos;s politeness rules, they are not asked a single question and they are left to say whatever they want; but the custom is to offer them lard or salt beef to eat. First they talk of the most varied subjects, except marriage; at the end though, the father (or the closest relative who has come with the young man) asks the girl&apos;s parents the question. At that moment, the gallant takes out of his basket the bottle of liquor (in the Lannion region it is bottle of white wine) and offers some of it to all the people present, of all ages and all sexes, except to the little children who haven&apos;t been woken up.]</font> <small> Paul-Yves S&eacute;billot, <a name="RDTP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RDTP"><cite title="source">Traditions et coutumes de Basse Bretagne</cite></a> (1904) 352</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
